{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "In order to distribute our thoughts and feelings, we must make intelligible and distributable copies of them.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "What they started became the most powerful means for the distribution, storage, and retrieval of knowledge in history, up until the invention of digital means.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "There has not been, however, an approach to the 'pre-printing' period in terms of the history of idea or intellectual history.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "I suggest that there is a rich field of study for printing history in the sophisticated concepts of reality that medieval and late Scholastic philosophy developed.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Distribution of our expressions of facts, thoughts, and emotions necessarily requires copying.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Yet scarcity itself was the condition of knowledge in Western societies before printing.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "The change specific to assembling more powerful processes for replication of text and image by impression altered the practices, and therefore the nature, of representation itself in the West.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Representation became more and more centered around mechanization; and thus the concepts behind representation veered closer and closer to and overlapped with the concepts behind replication.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Two of the easy but bad answers are techno-determinism, which elides the historical acts of persons as moral agents and therefore the need for moral responsibility, and theories of distributed agency (such as actor-network theory, object-oriented ontology, and panpsychism), which, although strongly diverging from one another, obscure the existential-historical situation behind the problems.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "A better theoretical approach to the aporias of communication is to study what the deeper and longer history of ideas that led to the start of mechanical replication because those ideas reveal the drives behind communication by distribution.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Scholars have not yet looked to the history of ideas in approaching the pre-history of print; and this has left a large untraveled territory behind what many scholars consider, due to the improbability of new discovery of early typographic fragments, to be the 'closed end' of the field prior to the middle third of the fifteenth century.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "The explicitly heroic image of Gutenberg, a product of printing historiography of the eighteenth, nineteenth, and early twentieth centuries, has been superseded, in part by the discovery that he did not complete the establishment of print technology by one stroke, in part by our understanding that it took a couple of centuries for the book to be transformed into the core of a print-oriented culture, in part through greater knowledge of early Asian printing, and in part through theoretical and factual re-evaluation of the cult of the Genius.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Truth and the Good it brings - the objects of inquiry and the motive for its passion - must somehow attach to what is distributed.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The notion of the copy, the power of mimesis, the whole range of relations of original to copy, of truth to what we know, and of the good to what we do, of the divine to who we are - all these run through the changes in distribution into what representation was in the development of knowledge in the West.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "One basic reason that scholarship has not explored the intellectual pre-history of print is also the compelling reason to turn in the direction of the history of ideas: as is evident by now, the facts about pre-typography and the earliest engraving are scarce.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "The history of ideas can reveal one kind of necessity that correlates an abstract problem with a desire that becomes a hungry drive across a society to express new meanings in new ways.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Multiplication distributes the thought that inspired the production; distributing these many products influences feeling and action as well as thought and brings into alignment in a readable way the activities of individuals and group in building, eating, worshiping, and communicating.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "The truth is what authorizes a person to make copies and gives the warrant to those who make or receive multiples to distribute them.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
